1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,340
Most project teams know what they need to
deliver. Far fewer have agreed on how

2
00:00:04,340 --> 00:00:06,455
they will work together to deliver it.

3
00:00:06,455 --> 00:00:11,988
That gap, between task clarity and
behavioral clarity, is where friction,

4
00:00:11,988 --> 00:00:15,139
confusion, and conflict tend to take
root.

5
00:00:15,139 --> 00:00:19,922
In this course, we'll explore how team
ground rules close that gap, and how to

6
00:00:19,922 --> 00:00:24,891
define, facilitate, document, and sustain
them across a project's full lifecycle.

7
00:00:25,891 --> 00:00:30,084
In this first lesson, we'll distinguish
team ground rules from general project

8
00:00:30,084 --> 00:00:33,786
policies and explain their role in
enabling productive collaboration.

9
00:00:34,786 --> 00:00:37,665
Let's begin with a distinction that's
easy to blur.

10
00:00:37,665 --> 00:00:42,516
A project policy is a formal rule or
procedure: how change requests are

11
00:00:42,516 --> 00:00:46,674
submitted, how risks are escalated, how
budgets are approved.

12
00:00:46,674 --> 00:00:51,032
These exist at the organizational or
project-governance level, and they apply

13
00:00:51,032 --> 00:00:53,268
whether a team agrees with them or not.

14
00:00:55,268 --> 00:01:00,904
Ground rules are different. They are the
behavioral norms a team sets for itself:

15
00:01:00,904 --> 00:01:06,118
how members communicate with one another,
how disagreements are raised, how

16
00:01:06,118 --> 00:01:09,711
decisions get made when there's no single
authority.

17
00:01:09,711 --> 00:01:13,922
They describe how the team will work
together day to day, not just what the

18
00:01:13,922 --> 00:01:15,516
team is expected to produce.

19
00:01:15,516 --> 00:01:19,628
Ground rules are agreed behavioral norms
that govern how a team works together,

20
00:01:19,628 --> 00:01:22,528
distinct from project policies or
governance procedures.

21
00:01:22,528 --> 00:01:25,965
Ground rules are set by the team, for the
team.

22
00:01:25,965 --> 00:01:30,028
Because members participate in creating
them, they carry a sense of shared

23
00:01:30,028 --> 00:01:32,699
ownership that a policy document rarely
achieves.

24
00:01:32,699 --> 00:01:36,895
It's tempting to treat ground rules as a
soft formality, something that gets

25
00:01:36,895 --> 00:01:41,315
mentioned in a kick-off meeting and then
forgotten. But that underestimates what

26
00:01:41,315 --> 00:01:42,266
they actually do.

27
00:01:42,266 --> 00:01:45,192
The first thing they create is
psychological safety.

28
00:01:45,192 --> 00:01:49,853
When a team has agreed norms around how
disagreement is handled, or how quieter

29
00:01:49,853 --> 00:01:53,319
voices get heard, people feel safer
raising problems early.

30
00:01:53,319 --> 00:01:57,251
Research consistently shows that
psychological safety, the belief that

31
00:01:57,251 --> 00:02:01,809
it's safe to speak up without penalty, is
one of the strongest predictors of team

32
00:02:01,809 --> 00:02:02,607
effectiveness.

33
00:02:02,607 --> 00:02:06,924
Ground rules are a practical mechanism
for building that safety into the team's

34
00:02:06,924 --> 00:02:09,248
structure rather than leaving it to
chance.

35
00:02:09,248 --> 00:02:12,359
The second thing they do is reduce
ambiguity.

36
00:02:12,359 --> 00:02:17,490
Without agreed norms, every interaction
carries an implicit question: what are

37
00:02:17,490 --> 00:02:18,489
the rules here?

38
00:02:18,489 --> 00:02:22,986
Is it acceptable to challenge a senior
colleague's estimate in a team meeting?

39
00:02:22,986 --> 00:02:26,198
How quickly is someone expected to
respond to a message?

40
00:02:26,198 --> 00:02:30,634
These questions get answered one way or
another, but without ground rules they're

41
00:02:30,634 --> 00:02:34,849
answered inconsistently, by whoever
happens to have the most social authority

42
00:02:34,849 --> 00:02:35,625
in the moment.

43
00:02:35,625 --> 00:02:39,806
The third thing ground rules do is
support accountability without requiring

44
00:02:39,806 --> 00:02:40,315
conflict.

45
00:02:40,315 --> 00:02:45,241
When a norm has been agreed collectively,
calling it out when it's violated is not

46
00:02:45,241 --> 00:02:49,742
a personal criticism, it's a reference to
a commitment the whole team made.

47
00:02:49,742 --> 00:02:53,985
That shift from personal to collective
accountability changes how difficult

48
00:02:53,985 --> 00:02:56,336
conversations feel for everyone involved.

49
00:02:56,336 --> 00:03:01,090
Teams that skip ground rules don't avoid
the need for norms. They just allow them

50
00:03:01,090 --> 00:03:04,417
to develop informally, which means they
develop unevenly.

51
00:03:04,417 --> 00:03:09,219
Some members assume behaviors that others
find frustrating. Dominant personalities

52
00:03:09,219 --> 00:03:12,776
set precedents that quieter members feel
unable to challenge.

53
00:03:12,776 --> 00:03:17,487
Ambiguity about decision-making authority
gets resolved through whoever escalates

54
00:03:17,487 --> 00:03:20,903
fastest, not through a shared
understanding of the process.

55
00:03:20,903 --> 00:03:25,500
The pattern that tends to follow is a
slow accumulation of small frustrations

56
00:03:25,500 --> 00:03:28,101
that eventually surface as larger
conflicts.

57
00:03:28,101 --> 00:03:32,145
By the time the conflict is visible, it's
carrying the weight of everything that

58
00:03:32,145 --> 00:03:33,117
wasn't said before.

59
00:03:33,117 --> 00:03:37,304
That's a much harder conversation to have
than the one you could have had at the

60
00:03:37,304 --> 00:03:37,622
start.

61
00:03:37,622 --> 00:03:42,166
One last distinction worth making in this
opening lesson: "ground rules" and

62
00:03:42,166 --> 00:03:46,710
"working agreements" are often used
interchangeably, and for our purposes in

63
00:03:46,710 --> 00:03:48,164
this course that's fine.

64
00:03:48,164 --> 00:03:52,869
If there's a nuance, it's this: "ground
rules" tends to emphasize the behavioral

65
00:03:52,869 --> 00:03:57,216
norms themselves, while "working
agreement" tends to refer to the document

66
00:03:57,216 --> 00:04:01,027
that captures those norms in a format the
team can refer back to.

67
00:04:01,027 --> 00:04:03,535
We'll use both terms throughout this
course.

68
00:04:03,535 --> 00:04:07,470
When we talk about the process of
facilitating and defining norms, we'll

69
00:04:07,470 --> 00:04:11,515
generally say "ground rules." When we
talk about the artifact that records

70
00:04:11,515 --> 00:04:13,566
them, we'll say "working agreement.".

71
00:04:13,566 --> 00:04:17,786
In this course, we'll cover what ground
rules are, where they fit in a team's

72
00:04:17,786 --> 00:04:21,229
development, and how to facilitate,
document, and sustain them.

73
00:04:22,229 --> 00:04:27,129
By the end, we'll be able to design and
lead a ground rule-setting process for a

74
00:04:27,129 --> 00:04:30,913
real project team and adapt it for hybrid
or virtual contexts.

75
00:04:31,913 --> 00:04:36,574
In this lesson, we first distinguished
team ground rules from project policies,

76
00:04:36,574 --> 00:04:40,995
establishing that ground rules are
behavioral norms set by the team for the

77
00:04:40,995 --> 00:04:41,294
team.

78
00:04:41,294 --> 00:04:45,174
We then explored why they matter,
covering their role in building

79
00:04:45,174 --> 00:04:50,025
psychological safety, reducing ambiguity,
and enabling collective accountability.

80
00:04:50,025 --> 00:04:54,078
Finally, we introduced the distinction
between ground rules as norms and working

81
00:04:54,078 --> 00:04:56,387
agreements as the documents that capture
them.

82
00:04:57,387 --> 00:05:01,391
In the next lesson, we'll map ground
rule-setting to the right moment in a

83
00:05:01,391 --> 00:05:04,353
team's development, using Tuckman's model
as our guide.

